In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally.

I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

Der folgende Artikel beleuchtet die biologischen und soziokulturellen Modelle im Zusammenhang mit der Schlafstörung Insomnie. Das biologische Modell legt den Schwerpunkt auf genetische Informationen, die vererbt werden, sowie medizinische Aspekte der Gesundheit. Die soziokulturellen Modelle betrachten die Umweltbeziehungen und deren Anwendung auf ethnische Zugehörigkeit, demografische Merkmale und den sozioökonomischen Status. Diese Übersicht der Insomnie berücksichtigt diese Modelle und erläutert jede der ausgewählten Forschungsergebnisse, um sie den Modellen besser zuzuordnen. Die Erklärungen der Forschungsergebnisse und deren Befunde werden dann kritisch hinterfragt, um jeweils spezifische Stärken und Schwächen zu mentionieren.

Eine Schlafstörung kann als primäre Schlafstörung, Schlafstörung, die mit einer anderen psychischen Störung zusammenhängt, oder Schlafstörung, die mit anderen Problemen zusammenhängt, charakterisiert werden. Primäre Schlafstörungen sind Dyssomnien oder Parasomnien, während Schlafstörungen, die mit einer anderen psychischen Störung zusammenhängen, mit einer Axis-I- oder Axis-II-Störung in Verbindung gebracht werden können. Andere Kategorien von Schlafstörungen können durch medizinische Komplikationen oder den Konsum von Substanzen verursacht werden. Die Dyssomnien umfassen: Primäres Insomnie, Primäres Hypersomnie, Narcolepsie, Atembezogene Schlafstörung, Zirkadiane Schlafstörung und Dyssomnie nicht sonst spezifiziert (NOS). Während primäres Insomnie eine Komplikation beim Erreichen oder Aufrechterhalten von Schlaf darstellt, ist primäres Hypersomnie eine Schwierigkeit beim Wachbleiben über einen Zeitraum von mindestens einem Monat. Narcolepsie umfasst Kataplexie und/oder automatische REM-Schlafphasen. Während Dyssomnien sich auf das Ein- und Durchschlafen konzentrieren, betreffen Parasomnien Schlafstörungen, die mit verhaltensbezogenen Abnormitäten und/oder physiologischen Phänomenen verbunden sind. Parasomnien umfassen Albtraumstörungen, Schlafangststörungen, Schlafwandelstörungen und Parasomnien nicht sonst spezifiziert. Schlafstörungen, die mit einer anderen psychischen Störung zusammenhängen, beziehen sich auf Schlafschwierigkeiten aufgrund von Axis-I-Störungen (Klinischen Störungen) oder Axis-II-Störungen (Persönlichkeitsstörungen oder geistige Behinderung). Diese Übersicht konzentriert sich auf Insomnie und befasst sich somewhat mit primären Schlafstörungen im Allgemeinen im Zusammenhang mit den biologischen und soziokulturellen Modellen.

Das biologische Modell von Schlafstörungen konzentriert sich auf Gene, vererbte Faktoren und die physiologisch erworbenen Aspekte von Schlafstörungen. Neuronen im Hypothalamus, die Orexin enthalten, sind für die Regulation von Schlaf und Wachheit verantwortlich. Diese Studie experimentierte mit Mäusen und fand, dass es phenotypische GABAB-Rezeptoren auf den Orexin-Neuronen gibt, die spezifisch für Schlaf-/Wachzustände verantwortlich sind. Die Aktivierung des GABAA-Rezeptors löst Reaktionen aus, die den Schlaf fördern. Wenn er blockiert ist, kann dies zu verringerter Angst und zur Induktion von Schlaf führen. Der GABAB-Agonist (Baclofen) verlängerte die Schlafzeit (Matsuki et al., 2009). Solche Ergebnisse deuten darauf hin, dass Tiermodelle von Mäusen auf Studien bei Menschen verallgemeinert werden können. Dies zeigt, dass es eine genetische und Umweltbasis für den physischen GABAB-Rezeptor beim Menschen gibt. Ein Problem oder Fehlen dieses Rezeptors könnte die Fähigkeit einer Person beeinträchtigen, ohne Medikamente ausreichend zu schlafen. Die soziokulturelle Implikation dieser Studie ist, dass, wenn das Phenotypen vererbt wäre, dies den Schlaf regulieren könnte, und eine Veränderung des Rezeptors würde den Schlaf eines Individuums negativ beeinflussen. Dies hätte negative Auswirkungen auf Lebensbereiche wie Schule, Beruf und alltägliche Aufgaben, die monotone Aufgaben und Fokus erfordern.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should.

The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD.

CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play "Twelfth Night" appears to argue that while disguise can be useful for extended periods of deception, one must eventually shed that newly adopted guise or risk losing oneself in the process. The difficulty of ending a deception lies in the risk of isolation. Thus, one must ultimately choose between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with those around them. While some may react neutrally to discovering they've been deceived, others may take offense to the charade.

The topic of deception in gender role reversal is particularly fraught, as it raises numerous side issues, the most significant being why? Why does the subject feel the need to hide their own identity and adopt the guise of the opposite gender? In Viola's case, it is clearly a form of self protection: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…" (5.1.247-249)

Arriving in a foreign land, Viola feels compelled to disguise herself as a man to protect herself from potential attackers. Her plan works, but it also isolates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is so convincing in her guise that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love with her: "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138) Additionally, she must grapple with suppressed romantic feelings between her and Orsino: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me." (5.1.260-261)

While this may be a progressive stance, to a modern reader, "Twelfth Night" can be seen as illustrating how deception can help bring suppressed emotions to the surface, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Some passages suggest that these characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that Viola/Cesario's appearance forces them to confront. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia secretly harbor feelings for women? One might argue that this is unlikely, as Shakespeare's character Olivia seems more likely to judge others based on appearance alone.

This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia shifts her romantic affections from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: "A sister, you are she." (5.1.315)

The German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course, nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be fully accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provisions across the colonies were similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors.

The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast. Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did, however, invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing a system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.”

Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.

There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.

Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The classification of popular music has expanded over the past 100 years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters, most, if not all genres—rap, rock, country, jazz, folk, just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain. Arguably, the sub-genre of heavy metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past 40 years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions, although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre, people realized that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre, which was then followed by sub-sub-genres, and the chain continues until today.

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres, but like everything else, it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today, one must first understand what the metal movement is and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

Metal is, in many ways, a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more violence, more theatricality. Less primitivism, more chops; people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument, and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug-induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70s that led to people getting crazier, leading to them to make crazy, other-worldly records, using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark, visceral qualities, which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also, later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark, visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement: (Byrne)

These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down, supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier, darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones, so they put that song on The White Album.

Einige Jahrzehnte bevor die Surrealisten mit ihren traumhaften Werken zu malen begannen, widmete sich der Künstler Henri Rousseau bereits selbst dem Schaffen seiner Träume, sowohl wörtlich als auch metaphorisch. "Der Traum", ein 1910 entstandenes Gemälde des berühmten Post-Impressionisten, stellt nicht nur eine Frau dar, die in einem Land innerhalb eines Traums staunt, sondern auch Rourouschs eigene persönlichen Träume und Ziele als Maler wider. Seit er mit seiner Arbeit begann, träumte er von Anerkennung, Akzeptanz und Lob von anderen Künstlern und Kunstliebhabern und musste feststellen, dass er mit einem schwierigen inneren Dilemma konfrontiert war, um dieses Ziel zu erreichen. "Der Traum" ist Rourouschs Werk, das seinen langjährigen inneren Kampf am besten widerspiegelt: entweder sollte er sich an bestimmte Malstile anpassen oder diese imitieren, um von der kritischen Kunstwelt, die er so sehr verehrte, akzeptiert zu werden, oder er sollte sich kreativ unabhängig und einzigartig geben und seinen eigenen Weg gehen.

Bevor man "Der Traum" aus dieser Perspektive analysieren kann, muss man zunächst etwas mit Rourouschs biografischer Geschichte vertraut sein. Henri Rousseau wurde am 21. Mai 1844 in der Stadt Laval im Nordwesten Frankreichs geboren. Sein Vater war ein Zinngießer und Hardwarehändler, der "bürgerliche Wohlstand" genoss (Shattuck 47). Im Kindesalter erhielt er keine formale Ausbildung in den Künsten; stattdessen arbeitete er bis zum Alter von vierzig als gabelou, ein Angestellter des städtischen Mautdienstes, auch wenn er den Titel des douanier, eines Zollbeamten, erhielt (Shattuck 46). Der Tod seiner ersten Frau Clémence, der acht infantilen Kinder folgten, ließ Rousseau mit nur einer Tochter, Julia, und großer Trauer zurück (Shattuck 49). Er hoffte daher auf ein neues Leben und widmete sich dem Malen, um Trost und neue Anfänge zu finden. Im Gegensatz zu seinen zeitgenössischen Kollegen, die den Landbewohner in der Malerei sentimentalisieren und romantisieren, ist er im Grunde genommen ein Volksmaler und hat die Hoffnungen und Träume des durchschnittlichen Mitglieds seiner Klasse.

Rourouschs Obsession, von der Kunstwelt anerkannt zu werden, ist im Kontext nachvollziehbar: Er war nicht nur in den formalen Maltechniken ungebildet und begann seine Karriere in fortgeschrittenem Alter, sondern arbeitete zur gleichen Zeit wie viele andere talentierte und besser bekannte moderne Künstler. Obwohl er schon viele Jahre lang arbeitete, erhielt Rousseau erst um dieselbe Zeit, in der Matisse als Künstler Anerkennung fand, die verdiente Anerkennung für seine Kunst. Im Buch "Moderne französische Maler" behauptet der Autor Jan Gordon, dass die beiden, während sie technisch im Kunstbereich Konkurrenten waren, in Stil und Sujet, aber auch in ihren Motiven zum Malen unterschiedlich waren: "Matisse war ein Maler, der eine Angst vor dem Malen auf triviale Weise hatte, während Rourouschs Wunsch war, ein Bild so konventionell zu malen, dass er in die Société des Artistes Français aufgenommen würde" (92).

Viele große Denker haben eine enge Verbindung zwischen Ethik und Ästhetik, zwischen Wahrheit und Schönheit postuliert. Ich glaube, dass es auf einer grundlegenden Ebene einen Grund dafür gibt. Wie John Keats in "Ode on a Grecian Urn" sagt: "Schönheit ist Wahrheit, Wahrheit Schönheit - Das ist alles, was ihr auf Erden wisst und was ihr wissen müsst." Vieles, was wir im Leben lernen, geschieht durch Bildung oder Erfahrung. Dennoch scheinen wir Ethik und Ästhetik, wie Keats andeutet, ohne diese erwarteten Wege zu schätzen. Sowohl Ethik als auch Ästhetik sind Versuche, zu beschreiben statt zu vorschreiben. Unsere Studien über Moral und Schönheit sind meist Versuche, zu erklären, warum ein Kunstwerk oder eine Literatur schön oder moralisch ist, anstatt eine festgelegte Methode zur Beurteilung oder zum Schaffen guter Kunst oder moralischen Verhaltens zu bieten.
Genau genommen kann Kritik an Kunst oder Moral das Wesentliche des Guten oder Schönen nie vollständig erfassen. Ein Gespräch über den Wert der Mona Lisa von da Vinci könnte sich etwa um Konzepte wie Vordergrund, Hintergrund, Kontrast oder kulturelle Bezüge drehen, aber letztlich beschreiben diese nicht, warum es gute Kunst ist. Stattdessen hört man häufig den Satz "Es gibt einfach etwas daran" vor einer komplexeren oder kritischeren Erklärung, wenn man nach einem Lieblingskunstwerk oder -buch gefragt wird. Ich glaube, dass sowohl Kunst als auch Moral nie vollständig auf eine Beschreibung ihrer Qualitäten reduziert werden können. Wie Flannery O'Connor sagt: "Eine Geschichte ist eine Art, etwas zu sagen, was auf keine andere Weise gesagt werden kann - man erzählt eine Geschichte, weil eine Aussage unzureichend wäre." Egal, wie vollständig wir die Eigenschaften eines literarischen Werks beschreiben, es bleibt etwas Transzendentales zurück. Ich glaube, dass Ethik ebenfalls diese Eigenschaft hat. Wie Wittgenstein sagt: "Es ist klar, dass Ethik nicht ausgedrückt werden kann. / Ethik ist transzendent. / . Ich schlage vor, dass es dieses 'Etwas', dieses 'je ne sais quoi' ist, das die stärkste Eigenschaft von Kunst und Moral ist, und dass diese transzendentale Natur sowohl von Ethik als auch von Ästhetik eine Verbindungsstelle schafft.

Ich glaube, dass Moral und Kunst so eng miteinander verbunden sind, weil wir beide am intensiven Erleben auf einer noemetischen Ebene, wie Kant es ausdrücken würde, teilhaben. Sie beeinflussen uns auf einer Ebene, die erlebt, aber nicht vollständig erklärt werden kann. Diese Verbindung ist besonders stark, wenn es um die Kunst der Literatur geht. Wie Mekean sagt: "Was Literatur von den anderen Künsten unterscheidet, was in Wahrheit einzigartig an der Kunst ist, ist ihre moralische Qualität. Vielleicht sind moralische Standards für andere Künste wie Musik unangemessen, aber sie scheinen für Literatur so relevant zu sein wie für das Leben selbst. Leben bedeutet notwendig Werte. . . . Literatur ist uns wichtig genau weil der Werte, die wir dort finden."

Today's Germany is considered a strong force, a united country with its own unique culture, stretching from the shadows of the Alps in München to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. The same culture can be felt from Köln on the Rhine River, through the heart of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. Given this diverse culture, it is not surprising that Germany, as we know it today, has evolved from various sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are a subject of debate among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, who were previously known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought against the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first used the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he defeated the Gauls and clashed with Germanic tribes that often crossed the Rhine. He borrowed this term from the Gauls to distinguish between those they had conquered and those they had not. The origin of the name is uncertain; it may have come from the spear used in warfare, known as a ger, or from the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout," indicating the Germans were noisy (Names of Germany).

The early Roman historian Tacitus wrote in his 98 AD work "De Origine et situ Germanorum" about the origins of the Germans: "I consider them aboriginal, not mixed with other races through immigration or intercourse. For in former times, those who sought to emigrate did so by sea.... Who would leave Asia or Africa for Italy to go to Germany, with its wild land, harsh climate, gloomy demeanor, and appearance? Certainly not the Romans, at least not yet. They sent their conquests into Germania for goods and led occasional land campaigns but mostly returned to their vast empire. As the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded goods from their land and their skills by serving in the Roman army (Ozment, 2005, pg. 17).

Afterwards, I stared downwards, my mind blankly taking in the view before me. Without emotion, silently, I studied the object, but refused to connect it to any abstract understanding. Thoughts entered my mind and left almost as quickly as they arrived. My consciousness worked so smoothly and effortlessly that it seemed I had no thoughts of my own, just an active and fluid perception of what I was looking at.
Once, on the advice of an artist I worked with, I bought a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I had always wanted to learn to draw since I was six years old, and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to how the brain interprets lines. One technique the book teaches is to frame any picture with a square, thus simplifying an overwhelmingly detailed picture.
At that moment, staring at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't mentally impose that frame. I was so overwhelmed and awestruck that I could only stand and gaze in wonder. Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, and Italian Renaissance masters used a rainbow of colors. If I had any delusions of my perspective being worthy of the title "Artistic," then before me was the beginning of my work, the start of my story, "Work in Brown."
My fingers touched my chosen tool, my muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand moved through space, giving shape and form to what could have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, calm and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Pieces of matter broke away and dissolved into nothingness. My hand shook and jerked more anxiously the second time, smacking the handle of the toilet again. The offending brown package refused to budge, stuck like a slug on the bottom of the toilet.
Gripping the mop loosely in my hand, feet set a foot apart, a green tie knotted uncomfortably around my neck, I frowned as I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter left as a message for the suckers who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, some tranquil moments, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the end of the toilet paper, and began to wrap it around my hand like an oven mitt. Standing upright, then bending at the waist, my hand slowly dipped into the bowl, like a mother going into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are dying behind the wheel. Several factors come together to create this deadly vector of statistics for the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health explain that one facet of the problem is that the teen brain is literally not ready for the hazards of driving. Simple inexperience also lies at the heart of the problem. This inexperience not only causes more fatal accidents, but also a higher rate of vehicle rollover, speeding, and driving off the road.
Teenagers also fare far worse when they travel with their peers—which anyone with an iota of sense knows they do on a regular basis. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study that showed the following correlation: between the age of the passenger and the number of traffic accidents occurring.
California and other states have attempted to increase the safety of teen drivers by requiring temporary provisional licenses that limit the hours that teens may drive and prohibit other minors as passengers.
But provisional driver’s licenses are, in my opinion, stopgap measures. The real issue is that—as a group—the youngest drivers are, by all statistical markers, simply not able to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman has performed research suggesting a common desire among those under the age of 19-20 to take risks for the sheer thrill of the sensation. It makes sense then, to delay driving at least until the tendency to thrill-seek has begun to level out. If we continue to issue driver’s licenses to young teens, we will not only continue to see deadly accidents happening, but the death toll is likely to reach staggering proportions in the next few years. By 2010, the Baby-Boomer’s babies will be eligible to drive and millions of new teen drivers will ready to hit the road.
Legislation dealing with this issue would be reasonably straightforward. Schools could continue to provide driver’s education classes to begin the learning process for future drivers, but no one under the age of 18 could operate a motor vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued prior to granting a full driver’s license, and a certain number of practical driver’s training hours would still be required as well. The specific number of hours required could be based on the number of hours already required by the majority of states (in California, for example, that number is currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult.) Because the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform, national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and I believe effective—means of protecting teens across the nation.
The legislation I suggest is by no means a novel idea.

In the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to view all the trick films, of which there were fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films generally take advantage of creative editing to produce illusions. My film study generally focused on describing the poetics for the majority of trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier characteristics present in a few of the later films. Largely, the trick film at the turn of the century is set-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, features no camera movement, uses long and medium shots, and adheres to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, there are some films at the beginning of the twentieth century that dare to break these guidelines by introducing aspects such as multiple shots.
One of the most noticeable aspects that the trick films share in common is their filming in an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films, and drew its root from the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One of the limitations inherent in the use of the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side, and do not walk towards or away from the camera. Take, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they go out of the frame, the camera does not follow them.
The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This borrows from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the borders of the stage. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.
Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative usage of the trick films; most of them focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. Note, however, that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer’s eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single “shot” may actually be several joined together to produce the illusion of apparition or disappearing. Look carefully at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary’s severed “head” begins, even though the whole film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor aus Caroline war ein früher und leidenschaftlicher Verfechter des Republikanismus. Obwohl er hauptsächlich ein Landwirt war, seine Aktivitäten in der Politik haben ihn zu einem Mann gemacht, der für seine Hingabe und sein Engagement für persönliche Freiheit und Regierung bekannt war. Seine Hingabe an ein agrarisches System bildete die Grundlage seiner Überzeugungen über die Regierung. Es war sein Versuch, das, was er als die vorzüglichste aller Berufe betrachtete, zu erhalten und zu fördern, das seine Argumente zu Fragen der Souveränität, Verfassungsmäßigkeit und sogar des Rechtssystems färbte.

John Taylor glaubte, dass die Vereinigten Staaten eine großartige Gelegenheit hatten, ein ideales System zu schaffen, weil es keine native Tradition gab, die die Schöpfer der Regierung behinderte, was die Einrichtung eines Systems der Selbstregierung ermöglichte. Er glaubte stark an die natürlichen Rechte des Menschen und daran, dass sie alle ineinander verwoben sind, was bedeutet, dass, wenn eines verweigert wird, alle versagen und der Wert der verbleibenden verringert wird. Diese Rechte sollten daher außerhalb der Reichweite der Regierung liegen. Er behauptete, dass das, was einige als „Naturzustand“ bezeichneten, bedeute, dass diejenigen mit körperlicher Stärke und böser Intelligenz profitierten, dass dies aber in einer Zivilisation nicht der Fall sein sollte.

Um diese ideale Gesellschaft zu schaffen, glaubte Taylor, dass eine Regierung geschaffen werden muss, die das innere Gute und Böse des Menschen berücksichtigt. Taylor war in seinen Überzeugungen sehr starr in Bezug auf eine dualistische Moral. Er behauptete, dass „da die Regierung durch den Menschen ausgeübt wird, müssen alle ihre Tugenden und Laster menschlich sein“ (ebd., S. 167). Er definierte gute Prinzipien als solche, die privaten Besitz schützen, die Landwirtschaft verbessern und Kapitalismus abschrecken, und believed that a government founded in good principles would function equitably, regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be led by Habgier und Eigeninteresse. Eigeninteresse, believed, was für den Menschen in allem die Motivation, aber es wurde nur als böse betrachtet, wenn es darüber hinausging, die Schaffung einer Gesellschaft, die auf dem Gemeinwohl basiert, um Untergesellschaften, die auf Kosten anderer lebten. Eine gute Regierung war notwendig, um das natürliche Böse des Menschen zu bewahren, und selbst dann musste sie genau überwacht werden, um den Zusatz schlechter Prinzipien zu vermeiden.

Taylor, wie viele andere eifrige Republikaner seiner Zeit, appelierte an eine strikte Auslegung der Verfassung. Er wollte eine extrem begrenzt Bundesregierung, der keine weiteren Rechte oder Befugnisse erlaubt wurden, als die, die in der Verfassung ausdrücklich erwähnt waren. Er wusste, dass eine ausgedehnte Bundesregierung teuer war und daher wahrscheinlich despotisch. Allerdings glaubte er, dass eine einfache, buchstäbliche Auslegung gefährlich sei und ohne Rücksichtnahme auf die Absicht der Verfasser leicht korrupt werden konnte. Noch mehr, er betrachtete die Unabhängigkeitserklärung als das wahre Grundgesetz der Vereinigten Staaten, weil es das Land klarer als eine Gruppe von souveränen Staaten als eine Nation beschreibt.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a precipitous drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. That was a bit disheartening, and it is hard to say why that might have happened. With the onset of winter at a New England campus, there is clearly a drop in people commuting either by bicycle or by foot, which may account for some portion of the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester when everyone is very busy finishing schoolwork, processing grades, and so forth. Filling out the commuter log might just have slipped off the radar screen for many folks. In addition, December brings the onset of the busy holiday season and the resulting month-long break for students and faculty, during which time many do not even need to come to campus at all. Classes then resume for the spring semester in late January, perhaps also a clue to the low number of logs for that month. But none of that really explains the low number of submissions for February. One might also conjecture that any project of this type is going to have an initial burst of energy and excitement at the outset, which might then naturally decline. In an effort to combat this trend, we created the Carpool Challenge Week, a special blitz campaign in March to try and reinvigorate the initiative, which did result in an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we experienced was how to maintain project momentum in the face of both a natural decrease in engagement, but also the problem of holiday and semester breaks experienced in higher education. Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars. This is deeply embedded in our culture. Therefore, it is essential to provide incentives for engaging in alternative modes of commuting. We gave out a lot of prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see how some even larger prizes might have affected participation – such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could have also helped to combat the dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes didn’t really change during the course of the project. If the prizes, however, were to increase in value over the course of the project, that might have helped. The gift cards seemed to be more than adequate at the outset of the project, but if we had announced in December the addition of a couple of bicycles, and then in January the addition of a hybrid or electric car, one can only think that participating and engagement would have increased instead of decreasing.

Ein ETF (Exchange Traded Fund) ist eine Wertpapierart, die entwickelt wurde, um einen Index, eine Rohstoff oder einen Korb von Vermögenswerten nachzubilden, ähnlich wie ein Indexfonds, aber flexibler und wie eine Aktie an einer Börse gehandelt. Ein ETF bietet die Diversifikation eines Indexfonds und die Vorteile des Einzelaktienbesitzes wie die Möglichkeit, Short zu verkaufen, auf Margin zu kaufen und in einer Transaktion so wenige wie eine Aktie zu erwerben. Diese Vorteile sind äußerst ansprechend, aber die Verwaltungsgebühren von ETFs sind deutlich niedriger als die der durchschnittlichen Investmentfonds. Leider gibt es auch einige Nachteile, wie die Notwendigkeit, für jede Transaktion, die ein ETF betrifft, eine Gebühr zu zahlen, genauso wie bei einer Aktienorder. Ein weiterer Vorteil von ETFs ist die große Vielfalt der verfügbaren Fonds. Es ist immer eine gute Übung für den versierten Finanzinvestor, zu überprüfen, ob die genannten Vorteile wie die Diversifikation tatsächlich bestehen und in welchem Ausmaß sie bestehen. Für diese Analyse werden wir den ETF IHF untersuchen und ihn mit den Top 10 Holdings vergleichen, die den ETF ausmachen, um festzustellen, ob die Vorteile des Besitzes eines ETFs den Vorteilen eines diversifizierten Portfolios aus den zehn Aktien nahekommen und ob es bessere Konfigurationen der gleichen Aktien gibt, die ein optimales Sharpe-Ratio oder eine höhere Rendite bieten könnten.

Um den ETF zu bewerten, wäre es zu unübersichtlich, alle Holdings einzubeziehen, daher haben wir beschlossen, nur die Top 10 Holdings zu berücksichtigen, die 63,58% aller Vermögenswerte im ETF ausmachen. Hier sind die Top 10 Holdings und ihre jeweiligen Anteile am Gesamtvermögen.

Um eine Abschätzung zu erhalten, wie gut diese zehn Aktien den ETF IHF insgesamt repräsentieren, können wir die aktuellen prozentualen Anteile, auf 100% normalisiert, verwenden, um die Beiträge jeder Aktie zu einem Portfolio-Beta und -Rendite zu berechnen, wenn das Portfolio vollständig aus diesen zehn Aktien in dem Verhältnis bestünde, das der ETF durch seine Holdings festgelegt hat. Die Berechnungen von Beta und Rendite sind in der folgenden Tabelle enthalten.

Aus der folgenden Tabelle ist evident, dass die Rendite eines Portfolios, das nur die Top 10 Holdings enthält, 6,11% höher ist als die des ETF, was einem Anstieg von 16% entspricht. Es ist auch evident, dass der Beta der Top-Ten-Holdings 0,12 niedriger ist als der des ETF insgesamt. Die bisherigen Ergebnisse deuten darauf hin, dass ein Portfolio aus den Top 10 Holdings eine höhere Rendite mit einem niedrigeren Beta bieten könnte. Es besteht jedoch die Möglichkeit, dass die Mittelwerte dieser zwei Portfolios statistisch nicht signifikant voneinander abweichen.

Um zu bewerten, ob diese Portfolios statistisch unterschiedlich sind, wird die Standardabweichung jeder der Top 10 Aktien ermittelt und auf 100% normalisiert, um ihre kumulierte Standardabweichung mit der des ETF IHF zu vergleichen.

Traum-Land ist eines von Edgar Allan Poes selbst ernannten besseren Gedichten. In "Traum-Land" verwendet Poe den Begriff "Thule" in den Versen 6 und 56, den Mabbott auf Virgil zurückverfolgt. Virgil nutzte diesen Begriff in Bezug auf eine Insel nördlich von Britannien, die die Griechen als das Ende der bekannten Welt betrachteten. Es ist sicher, dass Virgil diesen Begriff verwendete, aber es gibt eine aktuellere Quelle, der man einige Anerkennung zollen muss. Poe war sehr an deutschen Autoren interessiert.

Dieser Zitat ist wichtig, weil es Poes Vertrautheit mit Goethes Schreiben zeigt. Karl J. Arndt, in seinem Buch "Poe's Polydore und Goethes Mignon", kommentiert die Ähnlichkeit der beiden Gedichte und kommt zu dem Schluss, dass Poe Goethe nachahmt.

Das Oxford Companion to English Literature erwähnt, dass Goethe ein gefeierter Dichter der poetischen Dramen "Faust" war, das in zwei Teilen veröffentlicht wurde, der erste 1808 und der zweite im Todesjahr von Goethe, 1832. Im poetischen Vers des zweiten Teils von Faust befindet sich ein kurzes Gedicht mit dem Titel "Der König von Thule". Dieses Gedicht handelt von einem König, dessen Frau stirbt, nachdem sie ihm ein Bechergeschenk gemacht hat. Nach dem Tod seiner Frau trinkt er schwer und weint um seine tote Königin. Schließlich entscheidet er, dass es an der Zeit ist, zu sterben, und gibt seine Besitztümer seinen Kindern, abgesehen von dem Becher. Er geht dann zu einem Felsen, wirft den Becher ins Meer, schließt die Augen und stirbt. Das Verhalten des Königs von Thule und die Beschreibung des Königs in "Traum-Land" sind sehr ähnlich, fast ein dunkler Doppelgänger von Poes Verlust und einer Krücke des Trinkens. "Faust" wurde auch von H. P. Gratton in die romantische Dramaturgie umgesetzt, was weniger als ein Jahr vor Poes Verwendung des Begriffs "Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" geschah.

Poe erwähnt Thule zweimal in seinen gesammelten Schriften. In "The Pit and the Pendulum" erwähnt er "ultima Thule", verwendet aber diesen Ausdruck in "Traum-Land" zweimal, als Einleitung und Abschluss des Gedichts. "Der König von Thule" und "Traum-Land" können als Begleitstücke gelesen werden. Im "Traum-Land" beschreibt der Sprecher das Land von Thule und wie es dunkel und einsam ist, er ist von toten Freunden verfolgt und sieht eine schattige Welt ohne Farbe. All diese Szenen würden in "Der König von Thule" von Goethe gelesen werden können, da er gerade seine Frau verloren hat, einsam ist und seine Willenskraft verloren hat, zu regieren oder sogar zu leben. Das gesamte Gedicht ist eine Beschreibung, als ob der Sprecher in Goethes Gedicht eingetreten sei.

Gothe war ein bedeutender Autor, den Poe hätte kennen müssen, selbst wenn es nur aus Respekt für Tennyson wäre. Poe sagte einmal, als er gefragt wurde, ob er Tennyson bewundere. Abgesehen von der Verbindung zu Tennyson wäre Poe durch die vielen Nachdrucke, die nach der ursprünglichen Veröffentlichung entstanden, mit Goethes Werk in Berührung gekommen.

Under California law, could a customer injured after falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages for showing the manager acted with malice when he was informed of the spill twice but did not clean it for half an hour because he was eating dinner?

A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To prove that punitive damages are justified, the plaintiff must show that the defendant's actions were committed with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm and that the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have known the potential harm of not cleaning the spill, as multiple D&D customers had been injured in this way before her accident. She can also argue that, despite knowing this, Martin still failed to clean the spill. However, her argument that Martin's actions were despicable is less convincing, but still reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and Martin still did not take appropriate actions to ensure store safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, of an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne he was on dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Mr. Martin of the spill, and he responded the same way. At 5:30 pm on the 13th, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Before Palmer's accident, five slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct that intends to cause harm, or absent intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and committed with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when committed with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff's rights when the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Four years ago, I took a course in Islam at CBC. One of the main topics of heated discussion in the class was whether or not Islam is a hostile religion. I believe that the question is even more relevant today than ever before. Looking back on the events since 9/11, I have personally observed mass media go from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance for Islam in America. I don’t think in 2001 we could have ever had a presidential candidate with the name Barack Obama, who has an obvious Muslim background in his family.

The Biography of the Prophet is intriguing to me because according to what I know of the history of Muhammad, the biography contradicts the personality of Muhammad. From what I know and learned in the past, I thought that Muhammad forced converts to Islam. He would conquer and take over tribes and then force them to take on the Islam religion. But according to the biography, Muhammad was written as a sort of Martyr, who was misunderstood and even humbled himself to others. After which one by one people came to see the ‘truth’ in his teaching and sought him out.

Also, there are some uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the ‘miracles’ of Muhammad. The most obvious is when he took mutton and milk and multiplied it so that there was more than enough for forty men. It is this style of writing that makes me believe the writers wanted Muhammad to be perceived as the humble prophet, who needed not to prove anything, but simply lived in truth and miracles. This sort of fallacy is the worst because it downplays the miracle and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it is like they are stealing and trying to take credit for the life and personhood of Jesus through Muhammad.

There are also a lot of stories in the biography that make it seem like part of their agenda is to provide proof of ‘witness’ or of how people ‘on their own’ converted to Islam. But the problem is that a lot of the stories are at least from a third party perspective. That is in the story the author illustrates that he heard from so-and-so who heard from so-and-so etc. I didn’t like this much because although their idea was that it provided proof of the truth of the stories, I thought it diminished the stories and made it seem all that more suspicious.

I think the thing that bothers me most about this work is that they try and exalt and lift up Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. But history contradicts the idea that Muhammad was a gentle and humble man, and I can’t help but think if Muslims today know the true history behind Muhammad’s rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and the beliefs he held during his lifetime were immediately left behind in the development of Christian thought that moved forward after his life. If we look at this history in broad strokes, we see a trend of Christianity straying farther and farther from its origin. It seems that today’s world shows an ever-growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditional people remain and will resist any kind of thinking beyond what was taught to them, this portion of the population may not be prominent enough to influence the whole. Among Christians, a historical awareness will grow immensely in future years. A yearning will spread, to distinguish the doctrines that were added into Christianity over time from the actual intent of the religion’s namesake. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome will be inevitable: There will be a great reversal in the trend of Christian history. There will be a progression back to its original form. A movement will grow in numbers that will remove layers of doctrine, one after the other, just as if the clock started moving backward, until nothing is left except a conception of what Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God, before any other thinkers made such claims. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing masses in its wake to worship as if we were living at the time of Jesus, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, because the theological clock will have moved backward, the extreme proliferation of diversity in Christendom will reverse into more and more uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, between denominations, between divisions of every kind, we will see instead of differences, increasing similarities. Human history is filled with great reversions. Just one example is how Christians were at one time persecuted, shunned and killed by the Roman Empire. But later that empire became a Christian institution. Our country has gone from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play itself out in the arena of the Christian religion, undoing history in search of the source, and undoing diversity in the process. It is crucial to note that part of what will make this process possible will be a method of reading Jesus’ words as metaphorical, and not as literal statements. So what is it that happened since Jesus’ lifetime?

If we look far enough back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological beginning for the Christian religion. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures, were all at the core of the religion by the time the Romans assumed control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population did not share one spirit. They divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots and a majority of common people.
