I believe that The Jungle shows how human beings deep down inside are naturally greedy and self-centered. They only want to look out for themselves and make their lives as good as possible, but never look out for anyone lower than themselves. The Jungle shows this in many ways. The main obvious area is the owners and managers of the great factories. All they want to do is make their companies and factories as big and great as they can be. They do not care about anyone or anything that gets in their way or anything that gets hurt because of their advancements. According to Upton Sinclair's work, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". Sinclair is trying to paint a picture of the great damage that this pollution is creating. He shows that the owners have no regard for any person or animal that might get hurt. They do not care about the great plumes of smoke billowing out of the factories or the animal feces and urine runoff from the thousands of pens around Packingtown. The owners and managers also did not care about their employees working to make them rich. They would do anything to make or save an extra buck, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar". They force their employees to work awful hours and then without even a day's notice they might layoff multitudes of people at a time without any compensation or help finding a job. During the era The Jungle is set in there were not many, if any, laws or regulations protecting the workers safety or well being. This allowed the managers and owners to run wild, forcing their employees to speed up progress and work in terrible conditions. Although the book never says it directly, the people who lived and worked themselves to death in Packingtown were simply expected to deal with the horrible conditions both while working in the factories and living around them. There were no agencies or organizations set up to provide information or help to the workingman. There were unions that were formed, but these often did more harm than help as they made money off of the poor workers. The workers were so badly treated and had no way of escaping the system of Packingtown that they were described as slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors employ various techniques to evoke a certain feeling or attitude in their readers regarding important subjects. Some of these methods are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs a variety of these techniques in his novel "The Great Gatsby." Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an adjective with a noun in a way that is not commonly done to create a certain atmosphere around a subject. Other times, he assigns a meaning to a symbol and uses it for this purpose. Fitzgerald uses this latter technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In his novel "The Great Gatsby," F. Scott Fitzgerald imbued colors, particularly white/gray and red/pink, with meaning and later uses this meaning to evoke a feeling related to an important object.

Fitzgerald's use of white/gray signifies uniformity, with white being more refined and higher class and gray being older and faded. He established this meaning at the beginning of the novel by frequently using both colors. Daisy and Jordan are often "in white" (8), in fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears "white flannels" (41) at Gatsby's party, Tom wears a "white shirt" (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is "powdered milky white" (30). The only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is forming his impressions of Gatsby's party: "the halls... are gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors by coloring many mundane, unimportant subjects in white or gray: as Nick goes to work, he travels "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56), the names of people at Gatsby's parties are "gray names" (61) on Nick's timetable, Catherine's apartment is "one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses" — uniformity (28). He also describes ordinary people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a "white girlhood" (19) together, there are "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, the "Italian child" in the railroad is "gray" (26), and the dog-seller is "a gray old man" (27). Afterassigning enough meaning to white/gray, Fitzgerald uses them to signify unimportance or uniformity in certain subjects. This use of colors to convey something to the reader first appears with Daisy. After a significant absence of either color, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster"; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character, more like a uniform element, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald employs this technique around Daisy to reinforce the impression of her being a more uniform element, for example, there is a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18), and she is again in a "white" (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive due to its mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial demand for organic community-supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms offer tours of their operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This type of operation would allow the landowner to benefit from government programs while improving habitat, thus enabling recreational use and creating opportunities for farm tours and other programs to generate income or for educational purposes.

In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area due to the lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming can be more expensive than conventional farming. It requires more intensive labor and management to control pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often higher than with conventional methods. A small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices unrelated to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or open ground areas. Therefore, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise to maximize both profits and habitat quality.

The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It covers 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed but currently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals, many of which are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher, while others are declining and may soon be listed, like burrowing owls.

This area has been inhabited by Native Americans for centuries and was later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades. I selected a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations. As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I found an organic farm in the same area.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While understanding a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive for a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise.

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper.

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

Der Narr hat in seinem Herzen gesagt: "Es gibt keinen Gott." Diese Aussage findet sich zuerst im 14. Psalm der christlichen Bibel und ist auch der Ausgangspunkt für das Argument von St. Anselm zur Existenz Gottes. Diese Überzeugung scheint auch der andere Autor, den wir diskutieren werden, Thomas von Aquin, zu teilen. Weil beide ihre Argumentation zur Verteidigung desselben Konzepts vorbringen, und unsere Herausforderung darin besteht, den besseren der beiden Argumente zu bestimmen, müssen wir, um der Kürze halber, annehmen, dass beide in ihrer Überzeugung von der Existenz Gottes, insbesondere des Gottes der Bibel, recht haben. Ein Gott-Typus, der nicht dem ähnelt, an den unsere beiden Autoren glauben, würde uns nicht in der Lage sein, ihre beiden Argumente angemessen zu vergleichen, da sie beide im Wesentlichen die Verteidigung eines spezifischen Gott-Konzepts vorbringen. Dasselbe gilt für mich, dass beide ihre jeweiligen Punkte gut vortragen, keines von ihnen aber eine umfassende Basis für den Glauben an Gott bietet.

Um diesen Punkt zu veranschaulichen, werden wir zunächst das grundlegende Argument von St. Anselm untersuchen. Anselms Passage reflektiert einen Weg zur Verständnis durch den Glauben, indem man innerhalb sich selbst nach Beweisen sucht. Er erklärt, dass, weil Gott in unserem Verständnis existiert, wir seine Nicht-Existenz effektiv nicht konzipieren können. Während dieses Konzept, wenn es in seiner Terminologie ausgedrückt wird, etwas umständlich und manchmal unklar ist, liegt der Grundgedanke darin, dass der Beweis für Gott in unserem eigenen Geiste zu finden ist. St. Anselm schlägt uns vor, dass wir nicht über die Grenzen unserer eigenen Seele hinausgehen müssen, um Wahrheit über Gott zu finden; statt dessen finden wir die Existenz dieses Wesens einfach durch die Untersuchung dessen, was wir instinktiv für wahr halten. Fremde Beweise sind vermutlich nicht notwendig. Dieses Konzept des Akzeptierens dessen, wofür es keine unumstößliche empirische Evidenz gibt, wird in christlichen Texten oft als Glaube bezeichnet.

Dieser Gedanke unterscheidet sich stark von dem, den St. Thomas von Aquin vertritt. Aquinas meint hingegen, dass die Existenz Gottes vollständig durch Vernunft und empirische Evidenz bewiesen werden kann, ohne dass Glauben irgendeiner Art notwendig wäre. Eine solche Idee wäre in der Evangelisation, einem wichtigen Element des Christentums, von Vorteil, da sie es ermöglichen würde, neue Konvertiten zu gewinnen, ohne dass es auf ihre Bereitschaft ankommt, etwas Akzeptieren zu müssen, das nicht bewiesen werden kann. Sie könnten stattdessen durch Logik überzeugt werden. St. Thomas erläutert fünf verschiedene logische Argumente zur Unterstützung der Existenz Gottes: Veränderung, Kausalität, Kontingenz, Grade der Exzellenz und Harmonie. In jedem Fall zeigt er im Wesentlichen, dass der Beweis für Gott in der logischen Notwendigkeit für Gott liegt. Wenn man einem sagt, dass man ein fehlendes Puzzleteil vermisst, und die restlichen Teile des Puzzles zusammengesetzt hat, zeigt die Logik, dass man die Merkmale und die Existenz des fehlenden Puzzleteils kennen kann, ohne es selbst gesehen zu haben.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

The United States of America and Mexico are examples of two nations that were once plagued by a long-standing rivalry that lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, in which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, acquiring Texas and the American Southwest as new territory. Numerous other conflicts occurred between the two nations, finally subsiding just before the First World War. The rivalry began with Americans and Mexicans clashing over key issues such as religion, culture, and tradition, as well as significant material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31). This is similar to many other nations that have enduring rivalries with neighboring countries. Nations that share a border often have conflicts of interest that contribute to the creation of rival positions between the nations. The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations that share a common border. David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States. Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem that has plagued many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) states that “if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy” (p.86). Not unlike the Cold War, which was a rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union that included both an ideological struggle and a competition over interests deemed vital by each nation, the ideological struggles between the United States and Mexico were not based on political structure but rather on religious preferences. This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish. Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers posed a major obstacle to establishing friendly foreign relations between the United States and Mexico. Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry period. Most of the disputes during the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues related to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws from American border towns were a significant problem that persisted until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force along their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97). Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the latter part of the 19th century.

Twenty years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed.

I was a nurse at the time. I chose my profession out of a deeply ingrained need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. “You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick,” was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So—even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist—preferably a bit of both—I chose nursing.

Nevertheless, there I was: 46 years old and single, no money in the bank to speak of, and unable to work. I have been disabled ever since, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I have literally nothing left that I can call “mine.” I get by, but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, yet, there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. And believe me, when real disaster strikes, you do not feel very strong at all.

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life—big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well one prepares, some things are just too big to overcome alone.

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government’s “basket”; Lord knows it is moldy and falling apart, anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again—learning to help each other and to ask for help—rather than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters.

The Conservatives in the US talk about the “rugged individualism” that built this country; but in truth, what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism, it was compassion, mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit; first aid supplies, water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries, lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods, too. If you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food—do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you do not live in an apartment.

But while you are at it, get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms evolve in the manner that they do? Are there restrictions or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although D'Arcy Thompson stated in 1917 that “even now the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms,” the same can be said today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum, in combination with experimental studies, can be used to elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to delineate quantitative parameters that could in turn be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could be used to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies in order to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure that is a tube that travels over time through 360 degrees of space. These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl and is referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl of a shell is the last whorl (body whorl). The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture toward the viewer and with the apex pointing up.)

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has remained relatively steady for the past ten years. While the country is on track to meet many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as the water and sanitation targets, the rates of improvement for child and maternal health are woefully short of the improvements needed to meet their target goals by 2015. The multiple reasons for these shortcomings will be discussed below, and point to a need to strengthen the health system rather than focus on programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has made improvements in the number of births with a skilled health worker attending, with 72% of births now meeting this target. However, this category still includes traditional workers, such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions should the pregnancy be complicated (hence the large percentage of maternal deaths caused by hemorrhage). In other words, the improvements made in this particular indicator are somewhat misleading and there is still much work to be done. In addition, there has been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five years treated by a health professional. While data on postnatal care is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also of concern, with low rates across the country.

Cesarian-section rates are still lower than should be expected, around 4%. The cesarean rates additionally point to another concerning issue. While the rate of cesarean is 7% in urban settings, it is only 2% in rural. This points to the problem of equity of coverage across the country. Clearly access to healthcare services is focused around urban areas. Another issue of access concerns vertical equity. There is a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles. Clearly the poor are finding it much more difficult to access healthcare services, likely due to out of pocket costs.

In discussing next steps towards improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most basic question is how to most effectively address the lack of service. Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing on pre and post-pregnancy care for the mother and child. There is no question that programmatic approaches to solve the problems outlined above are attractive. Not only do “vertical approaches” that target one sector of improvements have much more targeted, manageable objectives, they also generally generate faster results. There are some drawbacks to keep in mind, however. One major drawback is that investing heavily in programming for one particular area of the health sector often means that funding for other areas suffers and human resources will flock towards working in that area that has more resources (the effect of international funding to HIV/AIDS and its effect on the family planning sector is one example). In addition, running multiple parallel programs for one area results in duplication of services that are also uncoordinated between programs. This leads to an increase in forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

Victorian novels are notable for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the aristocracy of the era. Two novels that deviate from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both works employ an element of mystery and a penchant for the unusual, which is atypical of the period's novels, thereby strengthening the characters within each work; they provide insight into their motivations and emotions.

“And now, a host of bewildering and confusing ideas crowded his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing; for the very words they said sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of firearms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which wore and tormented him incessantly.” (Dickens, 220)

Both novels often utilize this mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, though the content and function vary in each specific case. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences often reveal insights into Oliver’s inner layers, what troubles him, and his understanding of the true nature of the events around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, Oliver relives it vividly, as if in a dream, while he struggles to find help. The passage emphasizes Oliver’s lack of control over the events that unfolded, as well as the dire straits his health had come to occupy, which is strongly present in Oliver’s hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself overwhelms him, all his senses are numbed as he does not notice the “unseen hand” that bears him away; he experiences his despair again, removed from the shock of pain, as the pain is now constant and linked with fear rather than surprise. Oliver’s overwhelm raises the question of whose will brought about his misfortune, as it certainly wasn’t his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, not even attempting to influence the outcome of an event, even when his life is in danger. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also suggested, as if old Fagin has begun to break him, forcing him to accept this despair, affecting his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least for the sake of his own life.

“The day passed – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came – and night came again; a night so long and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours.”

Jahre ago arbeitete ich in einem Nachmittagsprogramm, das jüngeren Schulkindern Nachhilfe gab. Ich bemühte mich, ihnen in allen Fächern zu helfen, in denen sie Schwierigkeiten hatten, aber meine Stärken lagen in Englisch und Lesen. Ich wurde von einem der Instruktoren gebeten, einem kleinen Jungen namens Adrian, der in der dritten oder vierten Klasse war, zu helfen, der große Probleme beim Lesen hatte. Es wurde mir bald klar, dass etwas nicht stimmte; er hatte die seltsamsten Probleme. Einige Buchstaben konnte er perfekt aussprechen, andere nicht einmal annähernd. Er war lateinamerikanischer Abstammung, und ich war mir sicher, aber der Junge sprach perfektes Englisch. Wir kämpften weiter, bis ich eines Tages seine Mutter traf. Ich war dabei, einige Kinder zu betreuen, während der Rest der Nachmittagsgruppe auf einer Exkursion war, als seine Mutter hereinkam. Seine Mutter sprach kein Englisch, nur Spanisch. Mit meinem sehr schlechten Spanisch (ich war gerade erst angefangen) kommunizierten wir. Es wurde mir dann klar wie ein Schlag: Adrian konnte lesen, aber er wusste das Englische Alphabet nicht gut genug. Ich weiß nicht, ob diese Erkenntnis ihm je geholfen hat, aber ich hoffe, dass er jetzt besser dran ist.

Ich erzähle diese Geschichte, um das Problem der Sprachbarriere in Schulen, besonders hier in Kalifornien, anzusprechen. Ich erzähle sie auch, um zu zeigen, dass es nicht immer so offensichtlich ist, wie wir denken. Selbst für ein Kind, das perfekt Englisch spricht, kann das Lesen noch eine große Hürde sein. Jeder kann zustimmen, dass dieses Problem existiert, also was tun wir? In Adrians Fall war die Lösung relativ einfach: Nachhilfe in Englisch, insbesondere im Alphabet und in der Aussprache. Aber für die vielen Kinder, die kaum Englisch sprechen, ist die Lösung viel komplexer. Es gibt keine einfache Antwort. Die Kombination aus Zweisprachensystem, Mainstream-Immersion, privater Nachhilfe und ESL-Klassen ist der Schlüssel!

Von klein auf werden wir die meisten von uns gelehrt, dass es etwas da draußen gibt, das größer ist als wir, größer als wir es verstehen können. Einige von uns gehen zu Sonntagsschule, um darüber zu lernen, andere in eine Synagoge oder suchen in sich selbst nach den Antworten. Viele von uns nehmen die Religionen an, die uns von unseren Eltern weitergegeben wurden. Einige von uns lehnen sie jedoch rundheraus ab und behaupten, dass es nichts jenseits unseres eigenen, egozentrischen Universums geben kann. Wir können eine Werteordnung übernehmen und später unsere Meinung ändern. Egal, welchen Weg wir wählen, wir reisen, um einen Teil von uns selbst durch unsere eigene, einzigartige Perspektive der Spiritualität zu definieren. Wir suchen nach einem Licht im Dunkeln, um uns aus den Schatten ins Sonnenlicht zu führen.

“Ein Kardinal”, sagte mein Vater, als ich ihn fragte, welche Vogelart ihm am besten gefiel. Wir saßen auf der vorderen Veranda unseres Hauses und hörten dem trommelnden Regen auf dem Blechdach über uns zu, während wir Zigaretten rauchten. Die Dachrinnen brachten den Regen zu den Pflanzen am Rand der Veranda. Er sah hinaus in den Regen, ein Blick, der halb suchend, halb erinnernd wirkte. Er war in den letzten Monaten dünner geworden, und seine Kleider hingen lose an seinem Körper. Sein Haar war weniger geworden, dünner als ich es in Erinnerung hatte. Er sah noch immer hinaus in den Regen, evitarte den Augenkontakt. Ich fühlte mich allein, ängstlich und unfähig, mit meinem Vater über mein Bedauern zu reden, weil ich wusste, dass es das für beide noch realer machen würde. Ich umarmte ihn, setzte mich wieder hin, schob meinen Stuhl ein wenig näher an seinen und sah hinaus in den fallenden Regen der Juni-Dämmerung.

Mein Vater starb im Dezember desselben Jahres, fünf Tage nach meinem 22. Geburtstag. Die Chemotherapie und Strahlentherapie hatten meinem Vater nicht seine Schmerzen genommen, sondern ihn nur ein paar Monate länger am Leben gehalten als die Ärzte vorhergesagt hatten; welchen Nutzen hatte es, wenn er nur noch länger litt? Welcher Gott würde das tun, dachte ich. Allein in der Nacht betete ich nicht. Wenn Gott existierte, dachte ich, dann hatte er sich schon lange nicht mehr um mich gekümmert.

Ich wollte ihn nicht dabei zusehen, wie er aus diesem Leben in ein anderes ging. Also tat ich es nicht. Ich konnte nicht zusehen, wie das Leben, das mich geschaffen hatte, endete. Ich wollte meinen Vater daran erinnern, wie er gelebt hat, nicht wie er gestorben ist. Zudem wusste ich meinen Vater besser als seine Familie, besser als seine eigenen Kinder, und wusste, dass Dad nicht wollte, dass sein einziger Sohn Zuschauer bei seinem Tod ist. Ich rollte mich in eine Kugel in meinem Bett zusammen und wartete auf die Nachricht.

Niemand rief mich an.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, in essence and in name, an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt describes it in "The Rise of the Gothic Novel." The Gothic mode has been both disparaged and praised, accused of having no real depth, and lauded for its 'terrible sublime' aspect (Burke). The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's "The Castle of Otranto," used the ideas of both "the ancient and the modern" romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new method of literary expression. Walpole employs "old" theatrical elements and 'new' mimicry of nature in 'modern' novels to present what he terms "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre incorporates many throwbacks to medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even at the time of the publication of "The Castle of Otranto," the word "gothic" had been used to describe many different peoples, styles, and time periods. It was perceived as archaic or unsophisticated in the face of "modern" societal and literary "advancements." The combination of the more theatrical "Gothic" and the new format of the novel (allowing the reader a more personal view of the psychology of the characters) is what allows Gothic to remain for such a long time, and become at once obsolete and new to a reader much displaced in time from the original writing.

One of the most prominent gothic ideas present in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, the process of training a proper knight, is both retained and transmuted in the original Gothic novel, "The Castle of Otranto." Chivalry is especially important to Gothic writers because of what it represented—the classic knight, brave, honorable, competent—and the supposed or perceived lack of that ideal in contemporary society. Through the use of chivalric concepts and manners, the 'gothic past' is idealized and romanticized (hinting at the future evolution of Gothic to Romantic) and is used to attempt to improve the present. Walpole, when he wrote "The Castle of Otranto," was in the midst of a politically troubled time, and was despairing over the possible future. He, immersed in politics and (debatably) unfair accusations, may have begun to think, even if not explicitly, that the supposed morality and innate "goodness" in people present in the gothic era had been somehow lost in those individuals that made up the 'present' society. In his writing, this concept is clearly seen in several characters, one being the character Frederic. The reader can see before meeting Frederic that he embodies many chivalric traits, he is described as:

The description includes a great many traditionally chivalric images; Frederic is, foremost, a prince, he has suffered, been suitably affected by tragedy that he leaves, and is currently supposed to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is, of course, exaggerated, bringing the soon to be Gothic trope of excess into play (66).

The second key element in the supply chain management is supply. Supply is defined as the strategic decisions that should be made to determine the core capabilities of a facility and outsourcing partnerships should grow from these decisions. A company may have many different divisions of production for a single product. All division consists of different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must decide which division is a best fit for the different processes of the product. Management may also decide to outsource the work to other companies. The core reason a manager would outsource the work to companies is to create velocity. Velocity is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while at the same time reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Hitler ist in Burma lebendig, steht auf dem Schild. Ellen Page, die Schauspielerin von Juno, steht allein auf einer Straßenecke mit einem Karton über dem Kopf, auf den mit einem Sharpie die verstörende Nachricht geschrieben ist. Burma, auch Myanmar genannt, ist ein südostasiatisches Land, das von einem tyrannischen Militärregime regiert wird, das 1962 durch einen Staatsstreich an die Macht kam. Im Jahr 2007 kam es zu mehreren Straßenprotesten, den ersten öffentlichen Protesten seit einem Jahrzehnt. Diese Proteste wurden von einer großen Anzahl burmesischer Mönche angeführt und erhielten den Namen “Saffron Revolution”, benannt nach der Farbe der Roben, die die Mönche trugen. Nach den ersten Aufständen begann die Bevölkerung sich für die Proteste zu interessieren, und während die Regierung die Mönche zunächst friedliche Versammlungen erlaubt hatte, eskalierte die Gewalt bald zu einem Krieg zwischen den Mönchen und dem Militärregime. Monasterien im ganzen Land wurden von der Armee geplündert. Ausländische Journalisten wurden festgenommen und inhaftiert, und ein japanischer Fotograf, Kenji Nagai, wurde am 27. September 2007 einfach nur dafür getötet, dass er bei einem Straßenprotest anwesend war. Die offizielle Sterbetafel liegt bei 13 Toten, Colonel Hla Win, der einige Tage vor dem offiziellen Bericht aus der Armee desertierte, wird mit den Worten zitiert, “Viele mehr Menschen wurden in den letzten Tagen getötet, als du gehört hast. Die Leichen können in mehreren tausend gezählt werden.”

Das ist nichts Neues. Während dies einige der jüngsten Beispiele von Misshandlungen in der Welt sind, hat ein Staat das Ziel, Dissens zu unterdrücken und vollständige Herrschaft über seine Bürger zu behalten, so lang wie Zivilisation existiert. Frühzeitige römische Kaiser erklärten sich selbst als von den Göttern auserwählt, über alle Aspekte ihrer Gesellschaft zu herrschen. Japanische Kaiser werden für Götter gehalten, die in unsere Welt gesandt wurden, um ihr Volk durch die Erfindung von Motorola-Handys und Seppuku zu Wohlstand zu führen. Unser gegenwärtiger Präsident, George W. Bush, führt wöchentliche Videokonferenzen mit Ted Haggard, dem Leiter von “Stupid People Worldwide”, einer Niederlassungsgesellschaft der Republikanischen Partei.

Einige der bekanntesten Beispiele solcher Handlungen sind Ereignisse wie der Protest am 4. Juni 1989 auf dem Tiananmen-Platz, bei dem Intellektuelle, Gewerkschafter und Studenten sich versammelten, um gegen die autoritäre Herrschaft der Regierung zu protestieren. Der Todesfall in diesem Fall schwankt stark, da die offiziellen Berichte der chinesischen Regierung zwischen 200 und 300 Toten angeben, während der chinesische Rote Kreuz zwischen 2.000 und 3.000 Tote meldet. Ein weiteres Beispiel ist der Völkermord in Ruanda in den 1990er Jahren, bei dem Hutu-Milizen, unterstützt von der Regierung, systematisch Tutsis und politische Moderate unabhängig von ihrer ethnischen Herkunft ermordeten. Hitlers “Drittes Reich”, eine Periode, die sich über mehrere Jahre und Länder erstreckte und bei der alle Menschen jüdischen Hintergrunds verhaftet und getötet wurden, ist ein weiteres extremes Beispiel.

Duke Ellington’s Erbe im Jazz resultiert zu einem großen Teil aus seiner Langlebigkeit und seinen kreativen Fähigkeiten, sein Orchester zu formen. Ellingtons Präsenz am Piano ist in vielen der für diesen Auftrag ausgewählten Kompositionen subtil, aber als Komponist war er hervorragend darin, reiche und komplexe Stücke zu schaffen, die die individuellen Fähigkeiten der Bandmitglieder zur Geltung brachten. Er schuf ein Framework, in dem ein Solist frei improvisieren konnte, schrieb eng orchestrierte Stücke und Phrasen, die auf den spezifischen Stil der Bandmitglieder abzielten, um musikalische Ideen hervorzuheben. Dadurch betonte er auch den Klang des Orchesters insgesamt und schuf kohärente und originelle Klänge, die zu jedem Stück passten. Ellingtons Meisterhaftigkeit in Bezug auf den Klang der einzelnen Spieler und wie sie in einem wachsenden Ensemble zusammenpassten, ermöglichte es ihm, einige der innovativsten und brillantesten Stücke in der Geschichte des Jazz zu schreiben.
Das Grove Music Lexikon, das Ellingtons Klang und Innovation bespricht, erwähnt Creole Love Call und die Verwendung der Stimme als „Jazz-Instrument“ über seine gesamte Karriere hinweg. Dies ist ein frühes Beispiel für Ellingtons Verwendung der Stimme, um Textur und Farbe hinzuzufügen, ohne die Lyrics zu behindern. Creole Love Call zeigt auch Ellingtons Fähigkeit, den Stil seiner Solisten zu ergänzen, was sich in seinem gesamten Schaffen widerspiegelt. Diese langsame, sorgfältige 12-taktige Blues-Komposition enthält sechs Strophen, wie folgt:
Strophe 1: Ein Call-and-Response zwischen Stimme und Holzbläsern, bei dem die Stimme zunächst glatt und melodisch beginnt und dann zu einem raueren Klang übergeht.
Strophe 2: Ein getöntes Trompeten-Solo, das die Grundmelodie ausbaut und mehrere blaue Töne betont.
Strophe 3: Ein weites Klarinetten-Solo in einer hohen Lage, begleitet von einer subtilen synkopierten Klaviereinleitung.
Strophe 4: Das gesamte Orchester wiederholt die erste Strophe mit einem Call-and-Response durch die Bläser- und Holzbläserabteilung.
Strophe 5: Der kletternde Chorus des Stücks, bei dem die Holzbläser nun den Call-and-Response in einer hohen Lage anfangen, begleitet von einem synkopierten Stop-Time von den Bläsern und Rhythmusinstrumenten.
Strophe 6: Eine Rückkehr zur Struktur der ersten Strophe, mit einem Call-and-Response zwischen Stimme und Holzbläsern. In dieser Strophe übernimmt die Stimme den „Growl“-Klang und soloisiert als Instrument.
Tag: Ein kurzer Tag mit einer vokalen Lauffigur und einem dissonanten Neuerungsende durch ein Posaune.
Ellingtons Verwendung der Stimme, um diesem Stück eine Dimension des Klangfarbtons zu verleihen, ist ein Beispiel für eine stilistische Eigenheit, die sein gesamtes Werk durchdringt.
In Hot and Bothered, aufgenommen ein Jahr später, kombiniert Ellington sein Talent für enge Orchestrierung mit seinem Gehör für Klangfarbe. Ein Call-and-Response-Phrase zwischen „Bubber“ Miley auf getöntem Trompeten und Baby Cox’s Scat-Singen verwendet die vokalen Elemente von Miley’s Spiel und die instrumentalen Aspekte von Coxs Stimme, um einen reichen und komplementären Klang zu schaffen. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) erweitert diese Ideen, da Ellington Joe „Tricky Sam“ Nanton, ein langjähriges Mitglied der Ellington-Orchester, effektiv einsetzt, um die Melodie auf getöntem Posaune einzuführen.

She had always felt the need for something, a desire that refused to be fulfilled. This yearning began when she was about 14, as she entered her teenage years, and it persisted even three years later, at 17. She had concluded that she wanted a person rather than a thing, yet she felt no interest in any boys. Some had been drawn to her, but no one appealed to her. She often questioned her own mind, trying to understand what could cause such a strange phenomenon in a teenage girl. Years of contemplation yielded theories, but none were satisfactory. So she lived her life, continually questioning her desires.

A typical day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were kind and calm, rarely arguing with each other or with her. The only disputes were about her asserting her independence and free-spirited personality. She was the daughter of a calm couple, but she counterbalanced their energies with her lively and fun-loving nature, making her very likable. She was also kind-hearted.

Today, however, was not a calm day. As she moved from room to room looking for inspiration, she heard a short scream from the kitchen. Her mother's beautiful voice echoed in her mind. She rushed into the room, panicking as she cried, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother on the floor, in pain, saying "Ow" in short breaths. Her mother's daughter ran to her side and placed a hand on her to help. "Ouch... sweetie, I... I need you to take me to the hospital." Her mother's words were rushed and strained, and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay, Mom. Just tell me where I can carry you." Her mother directed her hand, and in that moment, the daughter was grateful for the strength she had gained from her classes. She carried her mother to the car, placed her in the back seat, and drove.

The hospital was filled with the scent of disinfectant and sickness, but she was too focused on helping her mother to notice. She rushed her mother inside and called for doctors. They quickly wheeled her mother away, and her daughter was left to sit and worry.

Her mother had fallen off a step stool while trying to reach a vase from the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as indicated by a high “alternative Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Mediterranean diet and is characterized by a higher consumption of plant-based foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats) and fish, and a lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol intake is permitted.

Previous prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to the Mediterranean diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. Additionally, an intervention trial showed that the Mediterranean diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Previous studies did not specifically focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 without a history of CVD or diabetes, who were participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. The authors calculated an aMed diet score six times from 1984 to 2004 using self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the preceding year. More than 95% of nurses continued to participate throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. In cases where records were not available, cases were classified as “probable” and included, with approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for confounders (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, there were 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined). Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America descended into a devastating financial crisis. Unemployment rose, the housing market collapsed, and many of America's largest and most significant corporations were left in ruins. This economic downturn persists to this day, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis come about, and how can we prevent it? In short, the financial crisis was caused by selfish and naïve political decisions that pushed banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an immature and insufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwrite and repack these mortgages into CDO's and CDS's. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks found themselves short on capital reserves, and the chaos was transferred to the repacked mortgages they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.

The financial crisis had its origins in 1999 during the Clinton administration, as the President sought re-election by boosting his popularity. To achieve this, the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, setting the stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest mortgage underwriter, was under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans to low and moderate-income people and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes accurately predicted the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As introduced earlier, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the economic meltdown.

Many factors combined to send the economy into a downward spiral, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO's) were extensively used in the years leading up to the crisis, intertwining more sectors of the economy with the housing market. This led to U.S. households and financial markets in general becoming overly leveraged in the housing market, making them extremely vulnerable to even minor price changes.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had purchased these mortgage-backed securities were left in the lurch. The top five U.S. investment banks together reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, accounting for about 30% of the USA's GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold cheaply, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were saddled with $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, die Exposition. Das ist der Teil in deinem Story, wo du deine kleinen Autorenschwingen ausbreitest und in die Lüfte steigst, um alle mit deinem magnetischen, nein magischen Prosa zu beeindrucken. Oder der Teil, wo deine Leser einschlafen oder die "Zurück"-Taste drücken und deinen Namen verfluchen. Dr. Merlin hat sich schon oft dabei ertappt, ihre Tastatur anzuschreien, wenn sie sich in der Mitte von Too Much Information wiederfindet, und das nicht mal auf die spaßige Art.

Die Exposition ist nicht dein Freund.

Deine lieben Leser kennen bereits den grundlegenden Schreibtip, "Zeige, nicht erzähle," aber Dr. Merlin stolpert immer wieder in lange Passagen, in denen nichts passiert, oder noch schlimmer, zu viel. Die Exposition ist der kleine Teufel auf deiner Schulter, der dir sagt, die Geschichte aus dem Weg zu räumen, um zu den guten Teilen zu gelangen (nicht zu verwechseln mit dem Teufel auf der anderen Schulter, der dich auffordert, deinem Publikum jedes Detail aus der Kindheit deiner Charaktere zu erzählen).

Die Exposition bedeutet, dem Publikum zu erzählen, was passiert ist, normalerweise in einfacher Sprache. Im Film passiert die Exposition, wenn ein Charakter einem anderen eine Menge Informationen gibt, etwa wie im "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." Im Fiction ist der Autor der Erzähler.

Ein Beispiel sollte her. Wenn du eine Geschichte liest, wird dir erzählt, dass die Heldin ihren Geliebten an einem bestimmten Ort und zu einer bestimmten Zeit getroffen hat, dass sie in einer prächtigen Zeremonie heiratete und dass ihr Mann vor ihren Augen ermordet wurde. Du würdest nicht erwarten, dass diese ganze Sequenz zwei Seiten lang ist, während beide nur jeweils zwei Zeilen sprechen. Du würdest erwarten, dass der Autor Zeit auf die Charakterisierung des Ehemanns verwendet, indem er durch seine Rede und sein Verhalten zeigt, wie tief er seine Frau liebt, und dass die Heldin auf große und kleine Weise zeigt, wie sehr seine Gegenwart in ihrem Leben sie verändert und bereichert hat (vor allem, wenn die Geschichte später noch einmal erwähnt, dass dies der Fall war). Eine richtige Einführung in den Charakter des Ehemanns würde dir ermöglichen, emotional mit seinem Schicksal verbunden zu sein und einen Einblick in die Charaktere der Heldin zu erhalten: Was sie in ihm sah, wie tief ihre Bindung war, Hinweise auf ihre Gedanken und Überzeugungen und Träume, wie sie durch seine Augen gesehen werden, und so weiter. Du würdest um seinen Tod trauern und dich so mehr mit der Heldin verbunden fühlen.

Kurz gesagt, du würdest erwarten, dass du dem simplen Knochen der Story Fleisch gibst: "Sie haben sich getroffen, sie haben geheiratet, er starb."

Als Autor musst du das Fleisch liefern. (*blick auf das Metapher, seufzt, macht weiter*) Manchmal ist es verlockend, gewisse Dinge schnell vorbei zu bringen. Vielleicht führst du einen neuen Charakter ein und weißt, dass er früher in der Air Force war, jetzt der Nachtmanager einer Tankstelle ist, zweimal verheiratet, keine Kinder, am Wochenende angelt und insgeheim davon träumt, die Tankstelle zu besitzen. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*) Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two news reports from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was "live" was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The main story was about a man from Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, her name was not stated, but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mugshot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provided were that he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story.
The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a "black" man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a "white" child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned.
The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter.
The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a "teaser" so that you would stay tuned.
They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was a dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual amount of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was.
Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said "300" months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

Es gibt eine unzerstörbare, unumkehrbare Bindung zwischen Brüdern; eine Verbindung, die viele Emotionen birgt: Liebe, Stolz, Eifersucht und Grausamkeit, um nur einige zu nennen. Brüder verstehen einander besser als irgendjemand sonst in einer solchen Verbindung und sehen sich nur in ihrem Bruder. In den dunkelsten Momenten zeigt sich die wahre Natur dieser Bindung, sei es zum Guten oder Bösen. Wenn diese Emotionen klar werden, bringen sie eine große Last mit sich. Ein Teil des Verständnisses der Gefühle, die aus dieser Brudervereinigung entstehen, besteht darin, mit den Konsequenzen, die sie mit sich bringen, umzugehen. Wenn jemand einem Bruder in die Augen schaut und in ihm sein eigenes Spiegelbild sieht, erkennt er sich nicht so, wie andere ihn sehen, sondern so, wie er in Wahrheit ist. Seine Taten und die Folgen seiner Taten zeigen seinen wahren Charakter. Im "Scarlet Ibis" untersuchen zwei Brüder dieses Thema und all die dabei auftretenden rauen Emotionen. Auf ihrer vergeblichen Reise durch eine üppige, lebendig beschriebene Landschaft erleben sie bittere Enttäuschung und intensiven Stolz bis hin zum dramatischen Schluss, bei dem nur ein Bruder überlebt. Das Thema wird durch die direkte Charakterisierung des Protagonisten Doodle und seine Interaktionen mit seinem Bruder sowie durch die Perspektive des Erzählers ausgedrückt, die die komplexen Gefühle des Protagonisten und seine Sicht der Welt um ihn herum kommuniziert, die beide einen großen Einfluss auf seine Handlungen haben.

Die Handlungen des Protagonisten lassen sich auf ein einziges Gefühl zurückführen: Stolz. Von dem Moment an, als er und sein kleiner Bruder Doodle zum ersten Mal zusammen ausgehen, bis zu ihrer letzten, unheilvollen Expedition, empfindet der Protagonist Groll gegen Doodle. Er hatte sich einen Bruder gewünscht, den er alle seine weltlichen Fähigkeiten lehren könnte, wie "…das Atmen anhalten, rennen, springen oder Klettern in dem alten Frauenschwampf…" Er hatte sich einen Bruder gewünscht, der die Rolle von "…jemandem zum Wettrennen zum Horsehead Landing… und jemandem zum Ausharren in der oberen Astgabel des großen Pins hinter dem Stall…" einnehmen könnte. Offensichtlich sind solche Dinge unmöglich, da Doodle eine extrem schwache Herzmuskulatur hat, was seine Überlebenschancen stark beeinträchtigt. Selbst wenn Doodle am Leben blieb, war es fast ausgeschlossen, dass er an körperlich anstrengenden Aktivitäten teilnehmen könnte. Was für ein Schlag für den jungen Protagonisten, dessen Kopf voller wilden Fantasien war, dass all diese Träume in einem Moment zerschlagen wurden. Tatsächlich zeigt sich sogar, dass er ein gewisses Maß an Wut gegenüber dem kleinen Kind empfindet, als er daran denkt, ihn mit einem Kissen zu ersticken. Was für ein Kind hat den Verstand, um über Infantizid nachzudenken? Doch sein Herz schmilzt, wenn das kleine Kind ihn anlächelt. Ein solches einfaches Verhalten gibt dem Protagonisten so viel Hoffnung! Das zeigt, dass seine Überzeugung wahrscheinlich nicht sehr stark war. In Gedanken hatte er eine instinktive Liebe für seinen Bruder.

The human brain is a complex, creative information-processing system. As technology evolved from primitive to modern, so did the metaphors describing the brain. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. Keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited, and they can lead to incorrect conclusions.
Information processing begins with input from the sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the brain's algorithms in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For instance, when viewing a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing combines basic information like color, orientation, and where the object's borders are to determine that you're seeing a box. Top-down processing uses decisions made during certain steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing here might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a certain extent, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes should access it. For example, while your brain processes every blade of grass when looking down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. However, you might pick out your name even in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results are modulated by attention repeatedly.
To process information, the brain must first store it. There are various types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded, with different types of encoding for each sensory stimulus. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to how the printed word looks, phonemically, referring to how the word sounds, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once stored, information must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which holds information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a specific series of neurons for a short period. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain proteins.
There are numerous models of how knowledge is organized in the brain, based on how human subjects retrieve memories, in computer science, and in neurophysiology. The semantic network model posits that there are nodes representing concepts, and nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, "chair" might be linked to "table," which can be linked to "wooden," and so forth.

Aldous Huxley kritisiert die bevorstehende Bedrohung durch Technologie und diekapitalistische Struktur, die durch die Schaffung eines Dystopias in dem Roman Brave New World verstärkt wird. Seine Menschen schätzen Gemeinschaft über das Individuum, werden von Anfang an konditioniert, um sofortiges Glück über alles andere zu streben. Die Bürger erweisen sich als Figuren in einem größeren Spiel, die in eine Ideologie gefesselt sind, wie sie vom World Controller festgelegt wird. Durch die Betrachtung des Werkes unter Marxistischem Linsenschärfen zeigt sich die zugrunde liegende Skepsis des Autors gegenüber der Entwicklung dieser Systeme. Frequentielle Terminologie in Marxismus, wie Homogenität und Reifikation, verstärken die Idee, dass Huxleys Roman ein Kommentar zu den Fehlern des aufstrebenden Wirtschaftssystems aus seiner Zeit ist.

Kapitalismus wird durch die Verwendung der Marxistischen These der falschen Bewusstheit satirisiert. Es wird verhindert, dass die allgemeine Bürgerschaft wahre wirtschaftliche Beziehungen zu anderen Klassen erkennt, da sie hauptsächlich auf eigenen Gewinn bedacht sind. Dies ist das Ergebnis der ideologischen Beeinflussung des Proletariats und der alltäglichen Arbeiter, was durch die Konditionierung der Menschen in Brave New World deutlich wird. Die Common Klassen, Delta, Gamma usw., haben kein eigenes Selbstbewusstsein; durch Hypnopädie wird der Antrieb zum Konsum, zum Ausgeben, zur Indulgenz über alles andere verstärkt. Dies wird, wie bereits erwähnt, vom World Controller manipuliert. Hegemonie, im Wesentlichen die Idee, dass Gruppen sozialer Klassen von einer separaten Gruppe von Individuen völlig beherrscht werden, ist in diesem Fall offensichtlich. Die unteren Klassen sind sich der Manipulation nicht bewusst, sie „kaufen“ förmlich eine Ideologie, die diese Struktur unterstützt (d.h. Kapitalismus und Konsumismus). „Die oberen Klassen sind geboren mit der Fähigkeit, dies zu erkennen, tun aber nichts; wenige Alphas oder Betas tun mehr als ebenfalls ihre Rolle zu akzeptieren. Tatsächlich sind die Interaktionen der sozialen Klassen, wie weiter unten diskutiert, bedeutende Hinweise auf die Wahrnehmung der Ausbeutung des Kapitalismus.

Beziehungen zwischen ungleichen Individuen existieren in Brave New World nicht. Der Roman scheint sich weigern, die Charaktere zu unterscheiden - sie fehlen sogar bei den Hauptcharakteren an Tiefe. Vielleicht will Huxley andeuten, dass die Aufstiege von Technologie und Kapitalismus zusammen den Menschen ihre persönliche Freiheit und Ausdrucksmöglichkeiten nehmen. Liebe existiert nicht, noch die Extremen einer einzigen Emotion; Interaktionen werden flach gehalten, dargestellt durch die Bemerkungen der Männer über Frauen, hauptsächlich über ihre körperliche Qualität, und die ungenierten Kommentare der Frauen über ihre Erfahrungen, sozusagen. Außerdem zeigt die absolute Zustimmung ihrer Klasse in der Hierarchie die sozioökonomischen Auswirkungen des Kapitalismus. Ihre absolute Zustimmung zu ihrer Rolle in der Gemeinschaft ist ein Hinweis auf Marxistische Gedanken zum Proletariat, die falsch glaubten, dass sie über alles anderen überlegen sind, solange sie weiterhin konsumieren, gehorchen und sich den anderen anpassen.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a challenge. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room, pretty much at the easternmost limit of the campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such distant places as the Willard Building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially if the weather was bad, which it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by large tracts of unused land. Today, that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings like the new Creamery and new health services building, and is now surrounded by apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But a bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be designed to accommodate the needs of bicyclists.
